SIMPLE: perception
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Perception
<hw>Per*cep"tion</hw> <pr>(p⟦etil⟧r*s⟦ecr⟧p"sh⟦ucr⟧n)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>perceptio</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>perception</ets>. See <er>Perceive</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of perceiving; cognizance by the senses or intellect;
apprehension by the bodily organs, or by the mind, of what is presented
to them; discernment; apprehension; cognition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>The faculty of perceiving; the
faculty, or peculiar part, of man's constitution by which he has
knowledge through the medium or instrumentality of the bodily organs;
the act of apprehending material objects or qualities through the
senses; -- distinguished from <contr>conception</contr>.</def>
<rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matter hath no life nor <qex>perception</qex>, and is not
conscious of its own existence.</q> <rj><qau>Bentley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>The quality, state, or capability, of being affected
by something external; sensation; sensibility.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This experiment discovereth <qex>perception</qex> in plants.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>An idea; a notion.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir M. Hale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ ⟦ldquo⟧The word <xex>perception</xex> is, in the
language of philosophers previous to <persfn>Reid</persfn>, used in a
very extensive signification. By <persfn>Descartes</persfn>,
<persfn>Malebranche</persfn>, <persfn>Locke</persfn>,
<persfn>Leibnitz</persfn>, and others, it is employed in a sense almost
as unexclusive as <xex>consciousness</xex>, in its widest signification.
By <persfn>Reid</persfn> this word was limited to our faculty
acquisitive of knowledge, and to that branch of this faculty whereby,
through the senses, we obtain a knowledge of the external world. But his
limitation did not stop here. In the act of external perception he
distinguished two elements, to which he gave the names of
<xex>perception</xex> and <xex>sensation</xex>. He ought perhaps to have
called these <xex>perception proper</xex> and <xex>sensation
proper</xex>, when employed in his special meaning.⟦rdquo⟧</note>
<rj><au>Sir W. Hamilton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>perceptive</ent>⟦br⟧
